MURRAY VALLEY ENCEPHALITIS - AUSTRALIA (07): (NORTHERN TERRITORY)
*****************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>

[1]
Date: Wed 27 May 2009
Source: The Australian, Australian Associated Press (AAP) report [edited]
<http://www.theaustralian.news.com.au/story/0,25197,25545500-12377,00.html>


Second man dies from tropical mosquitoborne virus infection
-----------------------------------------------------------
A man from the Gold Coast has died in Darwin from a deadly mosquitoborne
virus [infection]. [The 83 year old man] is the 2nd person to die in Darwin
this year [2009] after contracting the Murray Valley encephalitis (MVE)
virus. The grandfather of 13 died at Royal Darwin Hospital (RDH) on
Saturday morning [23 May 2009] after spending time in Darwin's coastal
region, a spokesman for the NT [Northern Territory] Health Department has
confirmed.

MVE is transmitted by the common banded mosquito, which bites after sundown
in the 1st 2 hours of the night. About one person in 1000 bitten by
infected mosquitoes contracts the disease. One in 4 of these people die
from the infection.

In a funeral notice published in today's [27 May 2009] Northern Territory
News, the deceased man's family described his death as "unexpected."

A mango farmer died in March [2009] from brain failure after contracting
MVE at his home in Batchelor, 100 km [62 mi] south of Darwin. The 58 year
old farmer went into a coma 2 weeks before his death, but the NT health
department was widely criticised for only issuing a warning about the virus
on the day his wife decided to turn off his life support. The farmer's
death was the first from MVE in the Darwin region for almost a decade.

Initial symptoms of the virus include fever, drowsiness, headache, stiff
neck, nausea, and dizziness. There is tremor and seizures especially in
young children, with the virus in some cases progressing to delirium and
coma, leading to paralysis or brain damage.

The deadly virus killed a man in Western Australia last year [2008]. While
such fatalities are rare, doctors say people must cover up and avoid being
bitten because there's no specific treatment for MVE. A warning about MVE
was reissued when the 83 year old man contracted the disease, although the
NT Health Department did not alert the public to his death. The [man's]
family have asked for people to donate money for MVE research at the
Menzies School of Health Research instead of bringing flowers to his
funeral, to be held in the Gold Coast this Friday [29 May 2009].

[byline: Tara Ravens]

