******
[2]
Date: Wed 27 May 2009
Source: ABC News (Australian Broadcasting Corporation) Darwin [edited]
<http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2009/05/27/2582238.htm?site=darwin>


Department defends withholding death details
--------------------------------------------
The Northern Territory Health Department is defending its decision to
withhold information that a 2nd person had died from the mosquitoborne
disease Murray Valley encephalitis (MVE). An 83 year old Gold Coast man
died in Royal Darwin Hospital on Saturday [23 May 2009] after contracting
the disease, which kills one in 4 people infected with it. The man's death
followed the mid-March [2009] death of a Darwin mango farmer.

But while the health department has continually issued warnings about the
disease, including when [the man] was first diagnosed, it did not reveal
that he had died at the weekend [23 May 2009]. His death was only reported
in the media this morning [Wed 27 May 2009], after his family placed a
death notice in the Northern Territory News.

The head of the Centre for Disease Control, Vicki Krause, says she did not
immediately inform the public of the death so that his family had time to
grieve. But the deceased's widow has told the ABC she wants people to know
about his disease so they better protect themselves against mosquitos. The
Territory opposition leader, Terry Mills, says the public should have been
told about the death immediately so they can understand the seriousness of
the threat.

Dr Krause says she has made continuous public warnings about MVE. Following
this morning's [27 May 2009] media reports, the Department of Health and
Families put out a media release to again remind people to take precautions
against mosquitoes. The department says the 83 year old man was bitten by a
mosquito in a rural, coastal area near Darwin, where more than 13 000
common banded mosquitos have recently been caught. Tests are underway to
determine if they [are carrying the virus]. The department says other tests
have revealed the disease, along with another dangerous mosquitoborne
disease called Kunjin, is widespread across the Top End. However, only one
in 1000 people who are bitten by infected mosquitos will catch MVE.

